  • Clean the names
  • Remove excess stuff from the filename
  • Separate coverage into range and length by the /
  • Separate the new range into start and end by the -
  • Make those three new variables integers.
ab2 <- ab %>% 
  janitor::clean_names() %>% 
  select(file=number_file, gene, accession, coverage) %>% 
  mutate(file=file %>% str_remove("/data/SRR606249_") %>% str_remove_all("1\\.|\\.fq\\.gz|_output.*")) %>% 
  separate(coverage, into=c("range", "length"), sep="/") %>% 
  separate(range, into=c("start", "end"), sep="-", remove=FALSE) %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(start, end, length), as.integer)

Function to parse filename:

parsefilename <- . %>% 
  mutate(dataset=str_extract(file, "subset\\d+") %>% if_else(is.na(.), "full", .)) %>% 
  mutate(trim=str_extract(file, "trim\\d+")) %>% 
  mutate(assembler=str_extract(file, "spades|megahit")) %>% 
  select(file, dataset, trim, assembler, everything())

Calculating coverage

Toy problem

Now, the problem of coverage. Lets look at a simple toy example of two genes a (length 20) and b (length 15) with coverages along particular intervals.

toy <- tibble::tribble(
  ~start, ~end, ~length, ~gene,
  1, 5, 20, "a",
  11, 15, 20, "a",
  1, 4, 15, "b",
  2, 6, 15, "b",
  9, 10, 15, "b"
)
toy
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   start   end length gene 
##   <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <chr>
## 1     1     5     20 a    
## 2    11    15     20 a    
## 3     1     4     15 b    
## 4     2     6     15 b    
## 5     9    10     15 b

Clearly a has coverage 10 and b has coverage 8.

My first thought to tackle this problem is to group by gene and sum the differences between start and end.

toy %>% 
  group_by(gene) %>% 
  summarize(coverage=sum(end-start+1))
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   gene  coverage
##   <chr>    <dbl>
## 1 a           10
## 2 b           11

But this clearly illustrates the problem - it works fine in a but the intervals in b need to be reduced because the first two intervals overlap.

Use the plyranges package to treat these as ranges so you can reduce them.

library(plyranges)

First, see what this looks like as ranges.

toy %>% 
  as_iranges()
## IRanges object with 5 ranges and 2 metadata columns:
##           start       end     width |    length        gene
##       <integer> <integer> <integer> | <numeric> <character>
##   [1]         1         5         5 |        20           a
##   [2]        11        15         5 |        20           a
##   [3]         1         4         4 |        15           b
##   [4]         2         6         5 |        15           b
##   [5]         9        10         2 |        15           b

Now, reduce those ranges, separately by each gene/length.

toy %>% 
  as_iranges() %>% 
  group_by(gene, length) %>% 
  reduce_ranges()
## IRanges object with 4 ranges and 2 metadata columns:
##           start       end     width |        gene    length
##       <integer> <integer> <integer> | <character> <numeric>
##   [1]         1         6         6 |           b        15
##   [2]         9        10         2 |           b        15
##   [3]         1         5         5 |           a        20
##   [4]        11        15         5 |           a        20

Turn it back into a regular data frame.

toyreduced <- toy %>% 
  as_iranges() %>% 
  group_by(gene, length) %>% 
  reduce_ranges() %>% 
  DataFrame() %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  set_names(~str_remove(., "X\\.")) %>% 
  arrange(gene, start, end)

Compare this:

toyreduced
## # A tibble: 4 x 5
##   start   end width gene  length
##   <int> <int> <int> <chr>  <dbl>
## 1     1     5     5 a         20
## 2    11    15     5 a         20
## 3     1     6     6 b         15
## 4     9    10     2 b         15

To our original:

toy
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   start   end length gene 
##   <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <chr>
## 1     1     5     20 a    
## 2    11    15     20 a    
## 3     1     4     15 b    
## 4     2     6     15 b    
## 5     9    10     15 b

Now we can easily get coverage. While were at it, go ahead and add columns detailing the total number of ranges, and what those are, as a sanity check.

toyreduced %>% 
  mutate(ranges=paste(start, end, sep="-")) %>% 
  group_by(gene, length) %>% 
  summarize(ranges=paste(ranges, collapse=";"),
            nranges=dplyr::n(), 
            coverage=sum(width)) %>% 
  mutate(pct_coverage=coverage/length)
## # A tibble: 2 x 6
## # Groups:   gene [2]
##   gene  length ranges    nranges coverage pct_coverage
##   <chr>  <dbl> <chr>       <int>    <int>        <dbl>
## 1 a         20 1-5;11-15       2       10        0.5  
## 2 b         15 1-6;9-10        2        8        0.533

On the ABRicate data

Lets do this on our data.

abreduced <- ab2 %>% 
  as_iranges() %>% 
  group_by(file, gene, accession, length) %>% 
  reduce_ranges() %>%
  DataFrame() %>%
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  set_names(~str_remove(., "X\\.")) %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  mutate(ranges=paste(start, end, sep="-")) %>% 
  group_by(file, gene, length) %>% 
  summarize(ranges=paste(ranges, collapse=";"),
            nranges=dplyr::n(), 
            coverage=sum(width)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(pct_coverage=coverage/length) %>% 
  arrange(file, gene, desc(nranges), ranges)

Now:

  1. Group by dataset, gene, and trim, and add a column showing which assembler(s) detected this entry.
  2. Group by dataset, gene, and assembler, and add a column showing which trim length was detected this entry.
  3. Add a final column that concatenates these two. This will be used for coloring.
abreduced <- abreduced %>% 
  group_by(dataset, gene, trim) %>% 
  mutate(assemblers_detected=paste(assembler, collapse="+")) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(dataset, gene, assembler) %>% 
  mutate(trim_detected=paste(trim, collapse="+")) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(detected=paste(assemblers_detected, trim_detected, sep=";"))
